WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.689 --> 00:00:05.410
&gt;&gt;Michael is the president and co-founder
of E Pluribus Partners, which

00:00:05.410 --> 00:00:08.960
is a leadership training and coaching firm
that specializes in helping

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:12.940
leaders create what Michael describes as connection
cultures.

00:00:12.940 --> 00:00:16.440
Connection cultures increase employee and
customer engagement as well

00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:21.380
as profitability and innovation.
Michael has an established history as an executive

00:00:21.380 --> 00:00:24.430
in business
development, marketing, and investment banking.

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:28.020
He has held positions in top companies ranging
from Morgan Stanley to

00:00:28.020 --> 00:00:32.940
Charles Schwab to Texas Instruments.
Today Michael will be sharing his ideas from

00:00:32.940 --> 00:00:35.649
his best-selling book,
"Fired Up or Burned Out."

00:00:35.649 --> 00:00:38.859
In which he addresses how to reignite your
team's passion, creativity,

00:00:38.859 --> 00:00:42.300
and productivity.
And hopefully he'll also be able to share

00:00:42.300 --> 00:00:45.719
some ideas about what he's
learned about Google culture today.

00:00:45.719 --> 00:00:47.969
Please join me in welcoming Michael Lee Stallard.

00:00:47.969 --> 00:00:55.370
MICHAEL LEE STALLARD: Alana, thank you.
Let me ask all of you.

00:00:55.370 --> 00:00:59.159
How many of you have experienced times over
your career when you were

00:00:59.159 --> 00:01:03.282
energized?
You were -- you wanted to get to work in the

00:01:03.282 --> 00:01:05.269
morning, and when you got
there, the hours flew by.

00:01:05.269 --> 00:01:07.820
And by the end of the day you didn't want
to stop working.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:10.750
How many of you have experienced that?
Okay.

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:13.930
Just about everyone.
How about the opposite?

00:01:13.930 --> 00:01:17.510
Where you struggle to get to work in the morning,
and the hours pass

00:01:17.510 --> 00:01:20.290
slowly and by the end of the day you were
physically and emotionally

00:01:20.290 --> 00:01:22.860
spent?
Anybody experience that?

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:28.580
Once again, just about everyone.
What's the difference between the two environments

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:29.840
that produce that
effect?

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:34.200
That's what we're going to talk about today.
Okay.

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:37.510
What is the work environment that really energizes
people?

00:01:37.510 --> 00:01:41.080
Because the work environment that I think
we all know from our

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:43.830
experience that when we're in that environment,
we're just more

00:01:43.830 --> 00:01:47.180
productive and creative and research supports
that too.

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:52.460
Now I first became interested that in this
whole area of the work

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:55.490
environment and its effect on productivity
and innovation, when I was

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:58.610
Chief Marketing Officer for Morgan Stanley's
Global Wealth Management

00:01:58.610 --> 00:02:02.320
Group.
I wanted to, first of all, create an environment

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:05.180
where the people I was
responsible for leading were thrive.

00:02:05.180 --> 00:02:07.480
And secondly, I wanted to create an environment
where the people who

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:10.590
worked on the front lines of the business
where they would be more

00:02:10.590 --> 00:02:14.670
energetic and enthusiastic because I knew
if they were, it would result

00:02:14.670 --> 00:02:20.200
in a superior customer experience.
The practices we put in place helped us double

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:22.420
our revenues over two
and a half years.

00:02:22.420 --> 00:02:28.950
And I knew we were onto something special.
In 2002, I left Wall Street and founded E

00:02:28.950 --> 00:02:31.510
Pluribus Partners.
Now that's a very unusual name.

00:02:31.510 --> 00:02:33.190
A lot of people have a hard time pronouncing
it.

00:02:33.190 --> 00:02:38.140
And they ask me, you know, what's that about?
It's actually based on America's motto which

00:02:38.140 --> 00:02:42.980
is e pluribus unum.
A Latin phrase that means out of many, one.

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:47.741
Now I became very interested in this whole
area of the work environment

00:02:47.741 --> 00:02:52.870
because I came across some research that showed
over the last decade,

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:58.500
75 percent of American workers report that
they're not engaged in their

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:01.959
jobs.
That's over a hundred million people who are

00:03:01.959 --> 00:03:04.770
not achieving anywhere
near their potential.

00:03:04.770 --> 00:03:10.040
And of that group, about 15 to 20 percent
of them are what we describe

00:03:10.040 --> 00:03:13.790
as actively disengaged.
So that they're working against the interest

00:03:13.790 --> 00:03:18.440
of the organization.
Now that's a problem.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:22.610
I believe in the years and decades ahead,
it's going to become a much,

00:03:22.610 --> 00:03:28.550
much bigger problem for organizations.
Tom Friedman wrote the book, "The World is

00:03:28.550 --> 00:03:31.170
Flat."
Just -- the world is becoming we know from

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:34.239
our experience in the
workplace, the world is becoming a more competitive

00:03:34.239 --> 00:03:35.620
place with
globalization.

00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:39.120
The standards are going up all the time.
What do is you think is going to happen to

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:43.239
organizations that
75 percent of their workers not fully engaged

00:03:43.239 --> 00:03:44.940
in their work?
Not good.

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:48.709
It's going to be difficult for many of them
to survive.

00:03:48.709 --> 00:03:55.410
Now when I founded E Pluribus, I met a number
of individuals who became

00:03:55.410 --> 00:03:58.780
my business partners.
One was Jason Pankau.

00:03:58.780 --> 00:04:03.239
Jason is an executive and life coach to many
successful Americans.

00:04:03.239 --> 00:04:07.489
He's an expert on how the workplace environment
spills over to affect

00:04:07.489 --> 00:04:12.069
people's lives outside of work.
A really interesting perspective, Jason has.

00:04:12.069 --> 00:04:18.049
Carolyn Dewing-Hommes is part our team.
She had worked at Citigroup and studied corporate

00:04:18.049 --> 00:04:21.120
cultures of some of
the leading organizations in the world and

00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:24.050
brought some great insights
to our research.

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:26.970
Dr. Mitchell Dickey, who had taught psychology
at Yale and Purdue

00:04:26.970 --> 00:04:30.370
Universities.
He received the first research award given

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:35.250
on emotional intelligence
research by the American Psychology Association.

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:40.830
In our research, we looked at all the avenues.
We looked at businesses, governmental organizations,

00:04:40.830 --> 00:04:44.320
social sector
organizations like hospitals and universities.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:49.530
We even looked at sports teams to understand
why they thrive, merely

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:57.990
bump along and survive, or even die.
And as we laid out all the variables we -- time

00:04:57.990 --> 00:05:02.770
and again, we noticed
one factor that seemed to predict the rise

00:05:02.770 --> 00:05:07.640
and fall of organizations.
And we named that factor the force of connection.

00:05:07.640 --> 00:05:16.080
Now connection is -- it's like gravity.
In the absence of gravity, objects do what?

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:17.090
Anyone?
They?

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:23.240
Float, they drift apart.
In the absence of this force of connection

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:27.760
people drift apart.
But with connection they pull together.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:31.040
They're more trusting.
They're more cooperative.

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:37.010
They're more aligned with each other and with
the organization's goals.

00:05:37.010 --> 00:05:43.070
Now, connection has three distinct core elements
we found as part of

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:47.889
our research.
The first one is vision.

00:05:47.889 --> 00:05:51.010
Now vision exists when everyone in the organization
is motivated by the

00:05:51.010 --> 00:05:56.850
mission, united by the values, and proud of
the reputation.

00:05:56.850 --> 00:05:59.220
And we're going to talk about Google in a
minute.

00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:02.190
In fact, what I want you to do is you have
a handout that has the

00:06:02.190 --> 00:06:06.500
definitions that has some blanks in it.
I want to you fill in the blanks because you're

00:06:06.500 --> 00:06:08.490
going to use it in a
little exercise.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:11.690
We are going to make this very specific to
Google in a few minutes.

00:06:11.690 --> 00:06:13.800
But I want to take you through the elements
first and then we'll talk

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:16.690
about how they apply.
So if you'll look at the sheet, fill in the

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:18.271
blanks as I go through the
definitions.

00:06:18.271 --> 00:06:25.290
One of my favorite examples of the element
of vision came during World

00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:29.110
War II when America was far behind Nazi Germany
in terms of military

00:06:29.110 --> 00:06:31.960
strength.
And General George Marshall, who was head

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:36.650
of the American Army, he was
focused on organizing the tasks of the military

00:06:36.650 --> 00:06:39.889
industrial complex
during that period.

00:06:39.889 --> 00:06:45.040
President Franklin Delano Roosevelt recognized
that something more was

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:49.040
required.
So he organized visits to the plants that

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:52.500
were producing tanks and
planes around America.

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:56.639
And on one occasion, he went to the Boeing
aircraft company up in

00:06:56.639 --> 00:06:59.690
Seattle.
And he brought with him a young pilot named

00:06:59.690 --> 00:07:02.800
Hewitt Wheless.
Hewitt was from Texas.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:07.680
And he asked Hewitt to tell his story to the
18,000 aircraft workers

00:07:07.680 --> 00:07:11.520
who were in attendance.
So Hewitt got up, he explained that he was

00:07:11.520 --> 00:07:16.539
flying his plane, and he was
surrounded by enemy aircraft who fired on

00:07:16.539 --> 00:07:19.750
him.
His plane was riddled with bullets, but miraculously,

00:07:19.750 --> 00:07:23.700
it held together
until he was able to safely return to his

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:28.060
base.
He thanked the workers at that plant for building

00:07:28.060 --> 00:07:32.330
the plane that saved
his life.

00:07:32.330 --> 00:07:38.669
Now, seeing that pilot thank them for their
work had a profound effect

00:07:38.669 --> 00:07:43.800
on the workers at Boeing.
It, in a sense, transformed them from factory

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:48.330
workers into freedom
fighters from an identity standpoint.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:53.490
Over the next four years from 1941 until 1945,
American aircraft

00:07:53.490 --> 00:07:56.930
manufacturers outproduced the Nazis by a rate
of 3 to 1.

00:07:56.930 --> 00:08:00.960
They produced nearly 300,000 aircraft during
that period.

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:08.210
Now when you think about this element, vision,
and how it applies to

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:14.030
Google, one thing that comes to mind is the,
the corporate motto "Don't

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:15.770
be Evil."
Let me ask you.

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:17.530
Does that connect with the a lot of people
here?

00:08:17.530 --> 00:08:20.889
I know when I first read that, I thought,
wow, that's really powerful.

00:08:20.889 --> 00:08:25.620
Does that connect with some of you? A few?
Now, you know, items of connection are not

00:08:25.620 --> 00:08:26.620
going to connect with
everyone.

00:08:26.620 --> 00:08:29.310
It's really going to depend on your personality
and your unique

00:08:29.310 --> 00:08:31.870
circumstances.
But that's one that really connected with

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:38.110
me was don't be evil.
The next element of a connection culture is

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:42.830
value.
And value exists when everyone in the organization

00:08:42.830 --> 00:08:46.810
understand the needs
of people, appreciates their positive, unique

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:51.430
contributions, and helps
them achieve their potential.

00:08:51.430 --> 00:08:55.610
Now that's rare in cultures today.
I think Google has one of the best cultures

00:08:55.610 --> 00:08:57.670
I've seen.
And we're going, as I said, we're going to

00:08:57.670 --> 00:09:02.980
talk about that in a minute.
A story that really illustrates this is -- happens

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:05.209
to be a story about
my favorite rock band.

00:09:05.209 --> 00:09:09.270
Now this band has been together for more than
30 years.

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:13.420
They've now received more Grammy awards than
any band in history.

00:09:13.420 --> 00:09:18.060
Any ideas who I'm talking about?
Any guesses?

00:09:18.060 --> 00:09:21.350
U2.
Yeah, you got it.

00:09:21.350 --> 00:09:25.890
Now U2's motto is "Everybody Gets Out of This
Alive."

00:09:25.890 --> 00:09:31.310
It's a very funny motto, isn't it?
If you know their story, it makes more sense.

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:36.529
Bono, the lead singer -- when Bono was 14-years
old, his mother passed

00:09:36.529 --> 00:09:41.130
away.
And he describes that period as feeling abandoned

00:09:41.130 --> 00:09:43.950
and alone .
His father was so grief-stricken that he wasn't

00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:46.600
able to comfort his
son.

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:51.170
So having experienced that, a few years later
when Larry Mullen, Jr,

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:56.360
the drummer for U2, when his mother passed
away when Larry was 16, Bono

00:09:56.360 --> 00:10:00.580
reached out to comfort him as a friend.
And said, "I know what you're going through.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:04.070
I'm going to be there for you."
And it started this friendship that's lasted

00:10:04.070 --> 00:10:11.880
until today.
Edge, the lead guitar player for U2, he went

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:16.940
through a difficult period
in terms of just experiencing divorce.

00:10:16.940 --> 00:10:22.160
And the band members were there for him to
help him get through that.

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:26.350
Adam Clayton, the bass player for U2, he suffered
through a five-year

00:10:26.350 --> 00:10:30.890
period with a drug and alcohol addiction.
And the band members actually reached out

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:33.510
to him to help him recover
from that.

00:10:33.510 --> 00:10:37.750
I think one of the most dramatic examples
of the commitment that the

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:44.060
members of U2 have to one another came in
the 1980s when the band was

00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:48.019
campaigning for the observance of a Martin
Luther King, Jr, day in

00:10:48.019 --> 00:10:52.570
America.
And they were about to play a concert.

00:10:52.570 --> 00:10:56.350
They received -- Bono received a death threat
that said if you play the

00:10:56.350 --> 00:11:00.660
song "Pride" or "In the Name of Love," which
is about the Reverend

00:11:00.660 --> 00:11:06.820
Martin Luther King, Jr, that you'll die.
The FBI thought that this was not a hoax.

00:11:06.820 --> 00:11:11.110
That it was a legitimate death threat.
But they weren't going to back down.

00:11:11.110 --> 00:11:18.570
They played the song.
And Bono closed his eyes as he sang the song.

00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:23.380
At the end of one verse, when he opened his
eyes, he found to his

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:28.589
surprise Adam Clayton was literally standing
in front of him to shield

00:11:28.589 --> 00:11:38.410
him from potential harm.
Bono has said that U2 is a great example of

00:11:38.410 --> 00:11:45.050
how to rely on others.
He said that he is a lousy guitar player and

00:11:45.050 --> 00:11:47.220
an even lousier piano
player.

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:50.950
He hears melodies in his head but without
his band mates, his talented

00:11:50.950 --> 00:11:55.440
band mates, he's not able to bring that music
to life.

00:11:55.440 --> 00:12:03.360
And so he appreciates their unique contributions.
It surprises many people to find out that

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:08.660
the economic profits from U2
are equally split five ways between the four

00:12:08.660 --> 00:12:14.980
band members and their
longtime manager, Paul McGuinness.

00:12:14.980 --> 00:12:20.710
These elements, these aspects of U2's -- the
relationships among the U2

00:12:20.710 --> 00:12:25.339
members -- create connection between them.
And that's helped them stay together for 30

00:12:25.339 --> 00:12:28.480
years so that they could
perfect their music over that time period.

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:39.120
I think of Google's culture.
And what elements in Google's culture represent

00:12:39.120 --> 00:12:43.579
value?
I think one that I learned about was that

00:12:43.579 --> 00:12:48.209
the average Googler goes
through about 120 hours of training a year.

00:12:48.209 --> 00:12:51.920
That's a lot of training compared to what
the employee in the average

00:12:51.920 --> 00:12:56.670
organization goes through.
So that is just one of many elements that

00:12:56.670 --> 00:13:01.339
show that Google values
Googlers.

00:13:01.339 --> 00:13:06.279
The next element in a connection culture is
voice.

00:13:06.279 --> 00:13:11.050
And voice exists when everyone seeks the ideas
of others, when they

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:17.720
share their ideas and opinions honestly, and
they safeguard relational

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:23.209
connections.
One of my favorite stories that illustrates

00:13:23.209 --> 00:13:27.800
the element of the value in
a connection culture comes from the Proctor

00:13:27.800 --> 00:13:32.829
 &amp; Gamble company.
In the year 2000, P&amp;G was really struggling.

00:13:32.829 --> 00:13:37.930
In one quarter, they lost $300 million dollars.
They -- half their brands were losing market

00:13:37.930 --> 00:13:41.860
share and talented brand
managers were walking out the door.

00:13:41.860 --> 00:13:45.540
Finally, the board at P&amp;G became frustrated
with the CEO. They made a

00:13:45.540 --> 00:13:50.120
change and they appointed a career employee
by the name of A. G.

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:53.070
Lafley.
And Lafley has confidence in the people of

00:13:53.070 --> 00:13:54.370
P&amp;G.
He worked there.

00:13:54.370 --> 00:14:01.300
He knew people all around the organization.
The first thing he did was he surveyed P&amp;G

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:05.620
employees to find out what
they thought he should do to improve the organization.

00:14:05.620 --> 00:14:08.980
Then he went and he travelled all around the
world and met with groups

00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:12.790
of employees.
And when he did, he said, we have moose in

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:17.970
our closets here at P&amp;G.
We have issues that we haven't been confronting.

00:14:17.970 --> 00:14:20.470
We need to get the moose out of the closet
where it's stinking up the

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:24.839
place and into the light of day on the conference
room table where we

00:14:24.839 --> 00:14:29.399
can deal with these issues.
And because I know the employees at P&amp;G, there's

00:14:29.399 --> 00:14:32.820
no -- if we put our
heads together, there's no problem we can't

00:14:32.820 --> 00:14:35.760
solve.
No code we can't crack.

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:39.360
And that's exactly what happened.
They rolled up their sleeves and they started

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:42.041
improving the company day
after day after day.

00:14:42.041 --> 00:14:48.680
Flash forward about 12 months, and according
to an internal survey that

00:14:48.680 --> 00:14:54.829
P&amp;G did, employee confidence in the leadership
and direction of the

00:14:54.829 --> 00:15:02.769
organization soared 250 percent.
In 24 months, P&amp;G's revenues and profitability

00:15:02.769 --> 00:15:05.890
soared.
Their stock price went up 75 percent.

00:15:05.890 --> 00:15:08.700
It created so much wealth that they were able
to acquire the Gillette

00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:18.240
Corporation, which was a huge acquisition.
Now think about that element of voice and

00:15:18.240 --> 00:15:21.279
how it applies to Google.
One of the first things that comes to mind

00:15:21.279 --> 00:15:26.530
is the TGIF's you have.
And how that brings the element of voice into

00:15:26.530 --> 00:15:30.160
your culture that helps
connect Google and Googlers.

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:37.199
Okay?
Now we're going to get to our exercise in

00:15:37.199 --> 00:15:39.550
just a minute.
But one more point I wanted to make before

00:15:39.550 --> 00:15:44.300
we get to the exercise is
that when these three elements are present

00:15:44.300 --> 00:15:49.820
vision, value, and voice, it
moves employees to want to give their best

00:15:49.820 --> 00:15:53.820
efforts.
And to align their behavior with organizational

00:15:53.820 --> 00:15:58.370
goals.
But it does more than that.

00:15:58.370 --> 00:16:05.519
When organizations are filled with disconnection,
it builds knowledge

00:16:05.519 --> 00:16:08.211
traps in the organization.
Let me just give you some examples of knowledge

00:16:08.211 --> 00:16:13.470
traps.
When, say, one regional sales group has a

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:16.800
lead that -- but it's in
another territory -- but it doesn't provide

00:16:16.800 --> 00:16:19.570
that lead to the other
territory because it views that territory

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:21.970
as competing with them,
that's a knowledge trap.

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:24.740
They have information that could help the
other group but they don't

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:28.621
share it because of this, in a sense, break
down in the relationship

00:16:28.621 --> 00:16:32.640
between the two.
When one employee, maybe an engineer has a

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:36.290
project and they have some
information that could help another engineer,

