In the book, we go much deeper.
But you get the picture.

00:33:36.289 --> 00:33:41.820
When I was immersed in all this research,
I had a personal experience

00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:47.619
that really helped clarify it for me.
In 2004, my wife Katie was diagnosed with

00:33:47.619 --> 00:33:52.469
advanced ovarian cancer.
And that was a year after she had been treated

00:33:52.469 --> 00:33:56.370
for breast cancer.
Now I'm delighted and relieved to say that

00:33:56.370 --> 00:34:01.169
Katie is cancer-free and
thriving today.

00:34:01.169 --> 00:34:06.740
In 2004, we experienced an outpouring of support
and encouragement from

00:34:06.740 --> 00:34:15.539
our family, our friends, and health care workers.
I'll never forget our first trip to -- our

00:34:15.539 --> 00:34:18.251
first visit to Memorial
Sloan Kettering Cancer Center in New York

00:34:18.251 --> 00:34:19.830
City.
Let me describe this.

00:34:19.830 --> 00:34:24.210
We were walking down the sidewalk and a big
doorman by the name of

00:34:24.210 --> 00:34:28.750
Nick, when we got within eyesight of the place,
he locked his eyes on

00:34:28.750 --> 00:34:33.179
Katie and greeted her like a returning friend.
And I thought how wonderful.

00:34:33.179 --> 00:34:36.480
This guy is -- he recognizes cancer patients,
probably because he's a

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:41.839
good wig spotter.
And he's intentionally connecting with them.

00:34:41.839 --> 00:34:46.639
And then we entered into the reception area,
and the receptionist is

00:34:46.639 --> 00:34:54.389
calling everyone honey.
Then the security people we met, the administrative

00:34:54.389 --> 00:34:58.500
people we met were
outgoing and friendly.

00:34:58.500 --> 00:35:01.839
We spent an hour with our oncologist and she
educated us about the

00:35:01.839 --> 00:35:05.130
various treatment options that we had to choose
among.

00:35:05.130 --> 00:35:11.720
And she answered our long list of questions.
She was upbeat and optimistic.

00:35:11.720 --> 00:35:16.070
And by the end of the day, I just felt like
I connected with these

00:35:16.070 --> 00:35:19.539
people.
And it made me more optimistic that we could

00:35:19.539 --> 00:35:23.799
get Katie through this
difficult season that was ahead.

00:35:23.799 --> 00:35:31.210
And we did.
As I thought about that experience, there

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:37.970
was a real aha for me.
I realized that connection is especially critical

00:35:37.970 --> 00:35:40.890
in the difficult
seasons we face in life.

00:35:40.890 --> 00:35:46.230
As individuals, and as organizations.
And a lot of people today are experiencing

00:35:46.230 --> 00:35:50.200
difficult seasons.
Both in their individual lives, and organizations

00:35:50.200 --> 00:35:52.510
are facing difficult
seasons.

00:35:52.510 --> 00:35:56.339
When people are connected, they tend to pull
together through

00:35:56.339 --> 00:36:01.619
adversity.
When they're not connected, the environment

00:36:01.619 --> 00:36:05.079
tends to become -- people
become isolated.

00:36:05.079 --> 00:36:09.650
They retreat.
They become more fearful.

00:36:09.650 --> 00:36:13.779
And finger pointing and distrust tends to
rule in organizations.

00:36:13.779 --> 00:36:18.150
And it makes it difficult to thrive and push
through adversity.

00:36:18.150 --> 00:36:26.710
[PAUSE]
Makes sense?

