It's nice to come to basically a session that's

00:37:40.519 --> 00:37:43.619
on connection and go
away with at least one new connection.

00:37:43.619 --> 00:37:51.539
So here are some things that research has
shown us will help increase

00:37:51.539 --> 00:37:55.440
connection in a workplace.
The first is role in the whole.

00:37:55.440 --> 00:38:00.460
When people understand the answers to four
questions, they feel more

00:38:00.460 --> 00:38:03.140
connected to the organization.
The questions are:

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:06.980
Where are we going?
Why is it important?

00:38:06.980 --> 00:38:10.849
How do we -- how are we going to get there?
And what's my role?

00:38:10.849 --> 00:38:14.869
So the more you can understand that for yourself
and help the people

00:38:14.869 --> 00:38:19.460
around you understand that, the more your
team is going to feel

00:38:19.460 --> 00:38:22.500
connected.
So how can you do that if you're not supervising

00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:24.630
someone?
Here's an example.

00:38:24.630 --> 00:38:29.520
If you read a good article --
I noticed in last month's Atlantic, there

00:38:29.520 --> 00:38:32.830
was a great article about
augmented intelligence in Google.

00:38:32.830 --> 00:38:35.580
In fact, you can probably see at the top it
says, "Google is Actually

00:38:35.580 --> 00:38:39.250
Making us Smarter."
I don't know if any of you saw this article,

00:38:39.250 --> 00:38:42.819
but it's a great article
that just shows how important your work is

00:38:42.819 --> 00:38:46.730
here at Google.
And if you had read that article, you could

00:38:46.730 --> 00:38:49.569
have circulated that to
your colleagues at work.

00:38:49.569 --> 00:38:54.240
And that would help them see why what you're
doing is so important.

00:38:54.240 --> 00:38:59.099
And that helps us connect through what we
call role in the whole.

00:38:59.099 --> 00:39:03.031
The second is finding the right role.
And that's so critical for all of us in life,

00:39:03.031 --> 00:39:05.279
isn't it?
When we're in the right role that's a good

00:39:05.279 --> 00:39:09.040
fit with our strengths and
provides the right degree of challenge, we're

00:39:09.040 --> 00:39:11.740
just energized.
And we perform better.

00:39:11.740 --> 00:39:15.510
We do better work.
Even more than that, though, we also, because

00:39:15.510 --> 00:39:18.750
we're doing good work
when we're in the right role, people affirm

00:39:18.750 --> 00:39:21.460
us, they give us
recognition.

00:39:21.460 --> 00:39:23.569
And that helps us.
Okay?

00:39:23.569 --> 00:39:30.059
So you can help the people around you find
the right role for them.

00:39:30.059 --> 00:39:33.060
When you're working with people you'll inevitably
see over time if

00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:36.779
they're in the right role or not.
And if you have a good relationship with them,

00:39:36.779 --> 00:39:38.350
you can provide them
honest feedback.

00:39:38.350 --> 00:39:41.819
Because it's ultimately honest feedback that
helps us find the right

00:39:41.819 --> 00:39:44.340
role.
So we need those people around us who will

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:47.529
provide honest feedback.
And if you're giving somebody that type of

00:39:47.529 --> 00:39:49.940
feedback, it's always good
to start out with praise.

00:39:49.940 --> 00:39:56.470
Like, Sara, you're great at this.
You may be even more effective if you try

00:39:56.470 --> 00:40:01.779
this.
And then when it comes to feedback, we all

00:40:01.779 --> 00:40:03.519
need that feedback
ourselves, too.

00:40:03.519 --> 00:40:08.670
And what I suggest is try to spend some time
with the people you're

00:40:08.670 --> 00:40:12.089
working with and get feedback on your work
product.

00:40:12.089 --> 00:40:16.109
And also how you interact with people one-to-one
and in a group

00:40:16.109 --> 00:40:20.730
setting.
And don't take too a specific feedback to

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:23.859
heart too much.
It's good to, number one, just listen to what

00:40:23.859 --> 00:40:25.599
people have to say.
Thank them.

00:40:25.599 --> 00:40:29.910
Don't be critical of what they say.
Write it down in a journal, keep track of

00:40:29.910 --> 00:40:32.650
it.
And then as you gather more feedback over

00:40:32.650 --> 00:40:35.670
time, patterns will start to
emerge and that will give you some things

00:40:35.670 --> 00:40:41.039
to work on.
Number three, connect as human beings.

00:40:41.039 --> 00:40:46.599
We just did the micro-connections exercise,
is what I call that.

00:40:46.599 --> 00:40:51.279
The truth is in most organizations, they're
not blatantly toxic.

00:40:51.279 --> 00:40:54.290
They may have their toxic moments at times,
but most organizations are

00:40:54.290 --> 00:40:59.230
not toxic cultures.
But they do, however, tend to be indifferent

00:40:59.230 --> 00:41:01.000
cultures.
They're indifferent to people.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:05.380
They tend to be so focused on the -- we get
so focused on the rhythm of

00:41:05.380 --> 00:41:10.849
tasks that we ignore people around us.
And that can be toxic, too, over time.

00:41:10.849 --> 00:41:15.059
It's like a low level of toxicity.
It's almost like oxygen deprivation.

00:41:15.059 --> 00:41:19.710
Where it effects us gradually over time but
there's a cumulative

00:41:19.710 --> 00:41:23.109
effect.
And we oftentimes don't know the effect on

00:41:23.109 --> 00:41:28.039
our bodies physically until
we've been in a toxic environment or in an

00:41:28.039 --> 00:41:31.369
environment that's
indifferent over years.

00:41:31.369 --> 00:41:38.250
The antidote for an environment that's indifferent
and subtly toxic is

00:41:38.250 --> 00:41:44.660
micro-connections like you did.
You know, asking a colleague a question that's

00:41:44.660 --> 00:41:47.410
unrelated to work.
Getting to know them as a human being rather

00:41:47.410 --> 00:41:54.670
than strictly interacting
as a human doing is a way to humanize the

00:41:54.670 --> 00:41:58.349
work environment.
Another thing we can could that falls in the

00:41:58.349 --> 00:42:02.890
micro-connections category
is just when we see people around rather than

00:42:02.890 --> 00:42:06.200
ignoring them when we
pass someone in the hallway, you can just

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:08.150
make eye contact or smile and
say hello.

00:42:08.150 --> 00:42:09.829
Little things like that make a difference
too.

00:42:09.829 --> 00:42:13.820
They start to make the -- Atul Gawande, the
surgeon who wrote the book

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:20.970
"Better," and he writes for the New Yorker.
One of the things he wrote about was asking

00:42:20.970 --> 00:42:24.940
unrelated questions.
That's his number one recommendations to -- recommendation

00:42:24.940 --> 00:42:27.200
to doctors
to improve their performance.

00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:31.109
And he had this great quote.
He said sometimes when we do that it helps,

00:42:31.109 --> 00:42:34.109
it makes the machine feel
less like a machine.

00:42:34.109 --> 00:42:39.609
It humanizes the workplace.
The next recommendation is grow or die.

00:42:39.609 --> 00:42:44.829
You know the definition for death in biology
is when an organism ceases

00:42:44.829 --> 00:42:47.430
growing.
We all need to grow.

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:50.579
We all need personal development plans in
writing.

00:42:50.579 --> 00:42:55.950
And so I would encourage you to do that.
Spend some time identifying how you're going

00:42:55.950 --> 00:42:58.540
to grow.
And the beauty of Google is you have such

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:02.890
a wealth of resources here.
All these G-to-G programs and formal training

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:06.890
programs.
And you if happen to find something that doesn't

00:43:06.890 --> 00:43:10.589
 -- an area you want to
grow in that there isn't a formal training

00:43:10.589 --> 00:43:14.660
or G-to-G offering
available, then start something on your own.

00:43:14.660 --> 00:43:17.079
Maybe you can find a book on the topic and
get a few colleagues

00:43:17.079 --> 00:43:22.200
together.
Or find an expert within Google who could,

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:26.980
who could teach a new class
that you could structure as a G-to-G offering,

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:28.660
or find an expert who
becomes your mentor.

00:43:28.660 --> 00:43:32.960
So these things are just ways to keep us growing.
Fist bumps moments.

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:36.640
Fist bumps are the high five of today.
I loved to see President Obama and the First

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:38.730
Lady giving each other
